From: spj@ukelele.gcr.com (Guru Aleph_Null)
Subject: Re: Linux BBS
Date: Wed, 3 Nov 1993 18:23:58 GMT

In article <1993Nov1.195652.7408@news.vanderbilt.edu> MCREYNPA@ctrvax.Vanderbilt.Edu () writes:
>In <wugBcc1w165w@questor.org> sp@questor.org writes:
>
>> arsenio@mobix.uc.pt () writes:
>> 
>> => I am looking for a BBS package that run with Linux. If you know any
>> => please Email me. Thanks.
>> 
>> Well, Waffle compiles fine under Linux, and costs around USD120.  There
>> is also UniBoard BBS available from Riccardo Pizzi in Rome, at a cost
>> of approx. USD20 per line (minimum USD40).
>> 
>> The UniBoard BBS is only available as binaries, and the current release
>> only runs on Linux up to 0.99pl12, I think.  I hope that the author will
>> soon release code that will work on later releases.
>
>Well, Waffle is neat and all that (coming from the MS-DOS world), but
>Waffle's principle use is as a BBS-style news gateway.  Given this, I
>can't figure out why the *hell* anyone who's running Linux would want
>to run BBS software to implement stuff that already comes with Unix.
>

Exactly. I guess that most people have been abused by MS-DOS for so
long, that the concept that the operating system is "its own BBS" is
totally alien.

>A much saner implementation would be to implement a BBS-style shell
>that calls that actual Linux applications for the user via a simplified
>interface.  This would prevent every bbs user from merely being user 'bbs'
>on the system and would allow Linux to do the things it was meant to do --
>like really being a multi-user OS.

Which is what I'm working on right now. I have a temporary menu in
right now, which is hard coded (along with terminal typing and the
multilingual stuff just isn't being used yet...) Its been slowed up
because I've been waiting for stuff to get to me via FTPmail. (Like
the IRC server... why bother with a cheezy chat system when you can
have the Limosine of Chat Systems?)  Everything I'm using is "out of
the box" stuff. Trn for "messages", IRC for "chat", Elm for "email", ,
'?' or 'help' puts you into the INFO system for hypertextual help.
(Granted, I've had to take some manual pages and format them into
Texinfo, but I see that as an improvement of the help system...) and
some of the usual Unix games like Moria for diversions...  Just to be
"stupid", the temporary menu displays the current date, phase of
the moon, and a new fortune after every iteration...

Hell, here's a snapshot of the cheezy thing:
==============================================8<====
November 03, 1993; Wednesday    The Moon is Waning Gibbous (84% of Full)
[Logname]: test2                [Full Name]: The Other Test User


Have you noticed that all you need to grow healthy, vigorous grass is a
crack in your sidewalk?
_____
Menu:
~~~~~
  'trn'          Threaded Read News
  'Pnews'        Post News
  'mail'         Read Electronic Mail
  'bash'         Run Bash Shell
  'help'         Help Using Emacs and Other Programs
  'moria'        Explore the Mines of Moria
  'moria-scores' Moria Scoreboard
  'fortune'      There's Contaminant in *my* COOKIE!
  'NC17-fortune' NC17 Rated Fortunes!
  'chat'         '/help' to learn how to use IRC (which isn't working yet)
  'quit'         Log Off System

['help' or '?'] Command>

--->8------------------------------------

And this is hard coded.  It needs some polishing for handling signals
better and doing some time accounting... Other crazy ideas are doing
things like maybe, making it "iScreen" aware, and letting the user
open up several simultaneous sessions...

>Anyway, the point of this post is to point out that someone not too long
>ago suggested implementing a BBS shell for Linux (via perl scripts perhaps?)
>and to ask how this is coming?  Has anyone gotten around to it?

I'm slowly building up to a climax if that's what you mean.. :)

>BTW, if you want a full-screen, curses-based, Searchlight(tm)-style BBS
>you might want to look at porting PBBS (Pirates BBS) which you should
>be able to find somewhere at msstate.edu (among other places).  But again,
>why run a bbs.  Why not just give out shell accounts and offer services
>via menus or some such?

Exactly. Pull no punches, stop wasting everyone else's time. But I
recommend getting a book about Unix security, clean up your system,
and etc.

